# How Does Climate Change Affect Our Health?  
## A Comprehensive Report  

---

### Introduction  

Climate change represents one of the most significant challenges to global public health in the 21st century. The Earth's average temperature has risen by approximately 1.5°F over the past century, a seemingly small increase with far-reaching consequences for climate patterns, ecosystems, and human health. These changes exacerbate existing health risks and introduce new threats, disproportionately affecting vulnerable populations such as children, older adults, marginalized communities, and those in developing countries. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of how climate change impacts human health, drawing on authoritative sources including the World Health Organization (WHO), the American Psychological Association (APA), and leading scientific literature.  

---

### 1. Physical Health Impacts of Climate Change  

#### 1.1 Heat-Related Illnesses and Mortality  

Rising global temperatures and more frequent, intense heatwaves increase the incidence of heat-related illnesses such as heat exhaustion, heatstroke, and cardiovascular stress. The elderly, children, people with chronic illnesses, and socially isolated individuals are particularly vulnerable. Heat stress exacerbates respiratory and heart diseases and contributes to approximately 1,300 heat-related deaths annually in the United States alone, with associated healthcare costs estimated at $263 million per year ([Urban@UW, 2021](https://urban.uw.edu/news/how-does-climate-change-affect-human-health); [American Psychological Association, 2021](https://www.apa.org/news/press/releases/2021/11/mental-health-effects-climate-change)).  

#### 1.2 Air Quality Degradation and Respiratory Diseases  

Climate change worsens air pollution through increased ground-level ozone, particulate matter from wildfires, and allergens such as pollen. These factors contribute to respiratory conditions including asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), bronchitis, and lung cancer. Wildfire smoke, rich in fine particulate matter, can travel far beyond the fire zone, causing both acute and chronic lung and heart diseases ([Delgado, 2021](https://www.discovermagazine.com/environment/how-does-climate-change-affect-human-health); [EPA, 2022](https://www.epa.gov/climate-adaptation/climate-change-and-public-health)).  

#### 1.3 Vector-Borne and Waterborne Diseases  

Climate change alters the geographic range and seasonality of vectors such as mosquitoes and ticks, increasing the incidence of diseases like malaria, dengue, Lyme disease, and West Nile virus. Warmer temperatures and altered precipitation patterns also elevate risks of waterborne diseases including cholera, typhoid, and diarrheal illnesses due to contaminated water supplies. The WHO projects an additional 250,000 deaths annually between 2030 and 2050 from heat stress, malaria, diarrhea, and childhood undernutrition attributable to climate change ([WHO, 2014](https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/quantitative-risk-assessment-of-the-effects-of-climate-change-on-selected-causes-of-death-2030s-and-2050s); [Medline, 2020](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/319699)).  

#### 1.4 Food Security and Nutrition  

Climate-induced disruptions to agriculture, including droughts, floods, and altered growing seasons, threaten food availability and nutritional quality. Increased atmospheric CO₂ reduces nutrient density in staple crops, while pest and weed proliferation necessitate greater pesticide use, posing toxicological risks to farmworkers and consumers. Food insecurity can lead to malnutrition, obesity, and associated chronic diseases ([Delgado, 2021](https://www.discovermagazine.com/environment/how-does-climate-change-affect-human-health); [Medical News Today, 2020](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/319699)).  

#### 1.5 Developmental and Neurological Effects  

Exposure to environmental toxins exacerbated by climate change, such as heavy metals and biotoxins from harmful algal blooms, adversely affects fetal development and neurological health. These exposures may contribute to cognitive deficits, lower IQ, and increased risk of neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson’s and Alzheimer’s ([Medical News Today, 2020](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/319699)).  

